      <hedline>
        <hl1>Stop Bullying Pakistan</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Sohail Murad calls on United States to stop putting pressure on fledgling democracies like Pakistan to violate their laws in name of swift justice, as is case with extradition request for Mir Amal Kansi, wanted in killing of two Central Intelligence Agency employees (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The United States Government should stop putting pressure on fledging democracies like Pakistan to violate their laws in the name of swift justice.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The United States Government should stop putting pressure on fledging democracies like Pakistan to violate their laws in the name of swift justice.</p>
        <p>Your June 19 news article makes clear that the Pakistani Government was pressured into violating its extradition laws to bring Mir Amal Kansi, wanted in the killing of two Central Intelligence Agency employees, back to the United States: there was no report of a judicial hearing to extradite a Pakistani citizen, which is required under Pakistani law.</p>
        <p>The United States should not violate its laws to please a foreign country; why should it ask other countries to do so?</p>
        <p>SOHAIL MURAD  Oak Park, Ill., June 19, 1997</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
